Dear Raving Maniac<br>
You know zilch about me or my service in 'Nam, yet you feel entitled to label me indifferent and feel just as free to hate me.  Forgive me, but I can't help thinking your perception of yourself as a &quot;damn good teacher&quot; is flawed, if you go off on somebody you don't even know like that.<br>
Let me help you out.  I teach too, and one of the things I teach is the history of our involvement in Viet Nam.  I do not present 'Nam vets as troubled, drug-using psychotics - after all I am one.  I do tell them about the tragedy of that war, and over the years I have received many moving letters from students who have heard my story (if you want to break down and make yourself known, I can send you some).<br>
I thought Oliver Stones movie was one of the worst on Viet Nam.  I do think that Apocalypse Now, flawed as it is, is one of the best.  Full Metal Jacket is not too far behind.  Garden of Stones is also a fine movie.  I don't think Hollywood has yet produced the Vietnam equivalent of All Quiet on the Western Front.  Bottom line:  the picture you present of &quot;the liberal media&quot; is grossly distorted by your own pre-conceived notions.  I seriously doubt &quot;every marine&quot; agrees with your point of view - nor would they with mine.  Marines, like all the others who served in the war, exhibit the same complexity of outlook found in the larger society.<br>
If you're so bent on presenting the Truth, how about presenting that?
